  "riddle": "1. Seek the railway station page for the Rajasthan town that sent us on this trail; from that page, what alphanumeric station code identifies the stop?\n\n2. There exists an article about the very town linked from the station page (follow the town link); from its infobox, note the year recorded as the town's establishment.\n\n3. How many ones appear in the base‑two (binary) representation of the founding year you just found?\n\n4. If you consult contemporary national statistics for the country that contains these places, what total population figure is listed for India?\n\n5. The district article linked from the town's page names its administrative centre—what town is listed as the district headquarters?\n\n6. In contemporary demographic tables, how many people are recorded as living in India according to an authoritative source you can cite on the relevant page?\n\n7. The iron ribbon that connects two desert cities has its own railway article—read it and report the total track length of that line in kilometres.\n\n8. Find the next prime number strictly greater than that kilometre length; what prime do you get?\n\n9. On another railway-related page you visit, an aside gives the country's headcount—what population figure for India does that source state?\n\n10. Now compute the sum of the digits in the population number you just obtained; what is that digit-sum?\n\n11. If you open the regional railway division's article linked earlier, which city is named as its divisional headquarters?\n\n12. The palace article linked from that city points to a lakeside urban centre—what is that city's elevation above sea level, in metres?\n\n13. The municipal article for a historic town in the same region provides geographic coordinates in its infobox—what coordinates are shown there?\n\n14. As an aside, count how many hospitals lie near the point 33.1934°N, 87.5601°W; what number of hospitals do you find?\n\n15. A page on the old princely realm records, under its most 